1 Learning objectives

  1. You can understand and explain how graphs are made of distinct layers of grammatical elements.

  2. You are familiar with the theory of the layered Grammar of Graphics as the foundation for the ggplot2 R package for data visualization.

  3. You can name and describe the 3 essential elements for building a graph with the ggplot2 package: data, aesthetics, and geometries.

  4. You can identify where to place the 3 essential elements as inputs in the ggplot() function.

1.1 What is the grammar of graphics?

We start with a discussion of a theoretical framework for data visualization known as “the Grammar of Graphics”. This framework serves as the foundation for the ggplot2 package which we’ll use extensively in this course.

Think of how we construct and form sentences in written and spoken languages (eg. English) by combining different elements, like nouns, verbs, articles, subjects, objects, etc. We can’t just combine these elements in any arbitrary order; we must do so following a set of rules known as a linguistic grammar. Similarly to a linguistic grammar, the Grammar of Graphics (GG) defines a set of rules for constructing statistical graphics by combining different types of layers. This grammar was created by Leland Wilkinson (Wilkinson 2005) and has been implemented in a variety of data visualization software platforms like R, but also Plotly and Tableau.

The Grammar of Graphics (GG) is a framework for data visualization that dissects each component of a graph into individual components, creating distinct layers. The package ggplot2 is based on the GG system, and allows us to build graphs step-by-step for flexible, customizable results.

The GG system dissects each component of a graph into individual components, which belong to seven distinct layers. We can take these different layers and combine them together to visually communicate information in our data.

GG layers have specific names that you will see throughout the course:

1.2 Components of the grammar

1.2.1 Essential components

At a minimum, we can break a graphic into the following three essential layers:

  1. data: the dataset containing the variables of interest.

  2. geometry: the types of geometric objects we can observe in a plot. For example: points, lines, and bars.

  3. aesthetic attributes of the geometric object. For example, x and y position, color, shape, and size. Aesthetic attributes are mapped to variables in the dataset.

The components of other layers that are “not required” are still important to think about, but you will be able to generate a basic plot without them.

To make a ggplot graphic, the data, aesthetic mapping, and geometry layers are the three basic required layers, while the other layers are for additional customization.

You might be wondering why we wrote the terms data, geom, and aes in a computer code type font. We’ll see very shortly that we’ll specify the elements of the grammar in R using these terms. However, let’s first break down the grammar with an example.

1.2.2 Gapminder data visualization

In February 2006, a Swedish physician and data advocate named Hans Rosling gave a TED talk titled “The best stats you’ve ever seen” where he presented global economic, health, and development data from the website gapminder.org. For example, for data on 142 countries in 2007, let’s consider only the first 10 countries in as a peek into the data.

Each row in this table corresponds to a country in 2007. For each row, we have 5 columns:

  1. Country: Name of country.
  2. Continent: Which of the five continents the country is part of. Note that “Americas” includes countries in both North and South America and that Antarctica is excluded.
  3. Life Expectancy: Life expectancy in years.
  4. Population: Number of people living in the country.
  5. GDP per Capita: Gross domestic product (in US dollars).

Let’s say we want to view the relationship between life expectancy and GPD per capita. Now consider this graph, which plots this for all 142 countries in the data frame:

Life expectancy over GDP per capita in 2007.

Let’s view this plot through the grammar of graphics:

  1. The geometric objects - visual marks that represent the data - are points.
  2. The data variable GDP per Capita gets mapped to the x-position aesthetic of the points.
  3. The data variable Life Expectancy gets mapped to the y-position aesthetic of the points.

What we have created is a simple scatterplot by adding together the following components: Not that though we did not explicitly specify a coordinate system, ggplot() will use Cartesian coordinates by default.

Now let’s add two additional variables to this plot.

Life expectancy over GDP per capita in 2007.

Let’s again view this plot through the grammar of graphics. The first thre components are the last as the last plot, but this time we have two additional aesthetic mappings.

  1. The geometric objects - visual marks that represent the data - are points.
  2. The data variable GDP per Capita gets mapped to the x-position aesthetic of the points.
  3. The data variable Life Expectancy gets mapped to the y-position aesthetic of the points.
  4. The data variable Population gets mapped to the size aesthetic of the points.
  5. The data variable Continent gets mapped to the color aesthetic of the points.

We built upon the simple scatterplot by adding variable colors and sizes:

The term data corresponds to the particular data frame where our data is saved and that x and y variables correspond to particular columns in the data frame. While type of geometric object considered in this example are points, graphics are not limited to just points. We can also use lines, bars, and other geometric objects.

Let’s summarize the three essential GG components of this plot in a table.

Summary of the grammar of graphics for this plot
data variable aes geom
GDP per Capita x point
Life Expectancy y point
Population size point
Continent color point

1.2.3 Other components

There are other components of the grammar of graphics we can control as well. As you start to delve deeper into the grammar of graphics, you’ll start to encounter these topics more frequently. In this lesson, we keep things simple and only worked with the three required components.

Other more complex components like position adjustments, coordinate systems, faceting, scales and themes are left for more later lessons. Generally speaking, the grammar of graphics allows for a high degree of customization of plots and also a consistent framework for easily updating and modifying them.

1.2.4 The ggplot() function

In this course, we will use the ggplot() function for data visualization. This function is included in the ggplot2 package of the tidyverse, which is an implementation of the grammar of graphics for R. As we noted earlier, a lot of terms the previous section was written in a computer code type font. This is because the various GG components are specified in ggplot() code. For the purposes of this chapter, we’ll always provide the ggplot() function with the following arguments (i.e., inputs) at a minimum:

  • The data frame where the variables exist: the data argument.
  • The mapping of the variables to aesthetic attributes: the mapping argument which specifies the aesthetic attributes involved.

After we’ve specified these components, we then add layers to the plot using the + sign. The most essential layer to add to a plot is the layer that specifies which type of geometric object we want the plot to involve: points, lines, bars, and others. Other layers we can add to a plot include the plot title, axes labels, visual themes for the plots, and facets (which we’ll use in later lessons).

The jargon used for GG elements and ggplot functions and arguments can be somewhat exhausting at first, but as you gain experience using these terms to making plots, you will become fluent in no time.

2 Wrap up

In short, the grammar of graphics tells us that:

A statistical graphic is a mapping of data variables to aesthetic attributes of geometric objects.

Let’s now put the theory of the grammar of graphics into practice.
